This paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it focuses on the control of bipedal locomotion. The use of Model Predictive Control (MPC) and the Divergent Component of Motion (DCM) are common techniques in robotics research, further supporting this categorization. The paper may also fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category as it deals with the control of a complex system (the bipedal robot). Additionally, the use of machine learning and optimization techniques in the proposed approach may place it in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the simulations and comparisons to state-of-the-art methods may suggest a Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
